And this is the week that we watched The Matrix.

00:17:31.940 --> 00:17:42.320
And the question, the quiz question on The Matrix was what gives Neo the experience, what happens to give Neo the experience of deja vu?

00:17:43.400 --> 00:17:43.520
Okay.

00:17:44.540 --> 00:17:50.320
So 80, yeah, 85% of them say he sees a black cat crossing twice.

00:17:50.660 --> 00:17:50.800
Right.

00:17:51.620 --> 00:17:51.920
Great.

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:55.220
I mean, that's like, that was the conventional interpretation, whatever, whatever.

00:17:56.620 --> 00:18:01.800
Another 10% or so will say the Matrix was reset.

00:18:02.460 --> 00:18:02.600
Okay.

00:18:02.740 --> 00:18:04.700
So they're actually, that's right.

00:18:04.820 --> 00:18:16.380
I mean, they're not wrong when they say that because the, the, seeing the cat move across was a symptom that was interpreted by those others as the Matrix being reset and the glitch in the Matrix thing.

00:18:16.480 --> 00:18:23.460
So they've just offered a deeper kind of structural explanation for, for the same phenomenon, but they're different answers.

00:18:23.460 --> 00:18:23.940
Right.

00:18:24.360 --> 00:18:26.520
And indicate different ways of thinking of the problem.

00:18:26.620 --> 00:18:40.380
Now, I also had a couple of people who said, um, when he saw the white rabbit tattoo, do you remember at the beginning of the movie when on his computer screen, it says, follow the white rabbit.

00:18:40.380 --> 00:18:43.560
And then like five minutes later, she turns and there's a white rabbit there.

00:18:44.500 --> 00:18:47.240
Now, those are unusual answers.

00:18:47.340 --> 00:18:49.520
That's not the majority of people, far from the majority.

00:18:49.520 --> 00:18:53.520
And it's an unconventional kind of reading, but like, is it simply wrong?

00:18:53.780 --> 00:18:54.180
Yeah.

00:18:54.180 --> 00:18:58.040
Like they're like, he uses the word deja vu in the moment with the cat.

00:18:58.420 --> 00:18:58.780
Yeah.

00:18:58.800 --> 00:19:01.560
He doesn't use it in the moment with the rabbit, but that's what happens.

00:19:02.020 --> 00:19:02.380
Yeah.

00:19:02.460 --> 00:19:07.480
And so like giving them the benefit of the doubt that they actually watched the rest of the movie and came to that answer.

00:19:07.540 --> 00:19:10.640
They're not like, it's an unconventional interpretation.

00:19:10.640 --> 00:19:18.840
And what I start thinking is like, even in these simple, straightforward, direct Q&A kinds of questions that there isn't just a right and wrong.

00:19:19.280 --> 00:19:21.280
Like it isn't, it isn't that easy.

00:19:21.460 --> 00:19:22.420
And who cares?

00:19:22.480 --> 00:19:25.840
It's one point on, on a quiz grade out of a hundred.

00:19:25.980 --> 00:19:27.040
So who gives a shit, right?

00:19:27.140 --> 00:19:35.540
Nevertheless, it's very interesting to see the different ways that people think and that the idea that these could all be equalized around the number one.

00:19:35.780 --> 00:19:38.300
They each got a one, they each got a question right.

00:19:38.420 --> 00:19:39.940
It's like, but not, not at all.

00:19:40.020 --> 00:19:41.800
Like they're so vastly different.

00:19:41.960 --> 00:19:46.960
Like if that, if the white rabbit one were followed through, you might be like, oh, this is really dumb.

00:19:46.960 --> 00:19:51.240
Or you might follow it through and be like, holy shit, this like remakes the movie for me.

00:19:51.320 --> 00:19:52.460
No, think about that.

00:19:52.620 --> 00:19:58.020
That moment of deja vu is the glitch moment that initiates the very movie, right?

00:19:58.140 --> 00:19:58.300
Yeah.

00:19:59.140 --> 00:20:00.560
Neo is an anomaly, right?

00:20:01.180 --> 00:20:06.120
I mean, that's a potentially interesting and generative mistake.

00:20:06.540 --> 00:20:06.860
Yeah.

00:20:07.180 --> 00:20:07.580
Yeah.

00:20:08.020 --> 00:20:11.400
But that's what I'm just thinking in terms of the equivalence version of math.

00:20:11.520 --> 00:20:13.500
Like I've committed, as we all do, right?

00:20:13.540 --> 00:20:15.520
Like we commit to a certain kind of quantification.

00:20:15.660 --> 00:20:26.580
And I find myself every single time I sit down to grades, 70 something quizzes, I find myself inevitably being like, ah, this right and wrong way that I set this up.

00:20:26.580 --> 00:20:29.360
It's just not a very, it's not very good way.

00:20:29.440 --> 00:20:35.160
Like it's efficient and I can get through it faster that way than like trying to figure out.

00:20:35.160 --> 00:20:41.020
But I wish there was some way that I could indicate like qualitatively, like this person answered the structural question.

00:20:41.180 --> 00:20:44.980
This person answered the deviant one in a deviant way.

00:20:45.120 --> 00:20:46.520
It's just simply not conventional.

00:20:46.640 --> 00:20:47.280
They're not wrong.

00:20:47.440 --> 00:20:51.520
But if there was some other qualitative way that I could add to those numbers.

00:20:52.320 --> 00:21:03.700
So to question your own type of injustice then, John, what would you, what would your reaction be to another instructor who gave the same exam, who saw that same response and without even thinking just marked it wrong?

00:21:04.160 --> 00:21:07.740
I would say my guess is the vast majority of instructors.

00:21:07.780 --> 00:21:08.040
Oh, yeah.

00:21:08.040 --> 00:21:09.940
See the white rabbit response and just mark it wrong.

00:21:10.540 --> 00:21:10.640
Yeah.

00:21:10.720 --> 00:21:11.640
You know, and...

00:21:11.640 --> 00:21:14.140
But what's your, but what's your, what's your response to that?

00:21:14.240 --> 00:21:16.020
Is it like dumb motherfuckers?

00:21:17.060 --> 00:21:18.240
No, I mean, I get it.

00:21:18.280 --> 00:21:22.500
Like I get the economic ways in which they're treating, you know, grading.

00:21:22.500 --> 00:21:26.340
And there are undoubtedly moments when I have that economic relationship to it too.

00:21:26.440 --> 00:21:27.480
It's like, I don't have enough time.

00:21:27.540 --> 00:21:28.440
I don't want to think about this.

00:21:28.480 --> 00:21:29.040
It's just wrong.

00:21:29.260 --> 00:21:32.660
But I always have a sense of an intellectual conscience about it.

00:21:32.720 --> 00:21:37.740
I'm always like, I am doing an injustice by simply assigning a number to this thing.

00:21:37.960 --> 00:21:40.260
I mean, I have that feeling in grading all the time.

00:21:40.460 --> 00:21:43.580
And it's really why, I mean, it's why I never give quizzes.

00:21:43.800 --> 00:21:47.340
I never ask right or wrong answers, like ever.

00:21:47.540 --> 00:21:48.400
It really is.

00:21:48.540 --> 00:21:56.420
And then I, like, I just have so much more flexibility over what the numbers do.

00:21:56.420 --> 00:22:03.320
I make the numbers do what I want them to do in terms of, like, motivating students to respond.

00:22:04.200 --> 00:22:06.780
And, you know, and, like, not, like, completely willing.

00:22:06.900 --> 00:22:13.380
There's always an attachment to, you know, what the numbers are and what I'm, what, you know, what they wrote.

00:22:13.820 --> 00:22:19.200
But there's, like, I steer clear of even trying to make some kind of determinant relationship.

00:22:19.200 --> 00:22:24.640
Because then you run into, like, the problems of, like, the technicality of it.

00:22:25.080 --> 00:22:30.600
I find myself wanting to distinguish exceptional work from just good work.

00:22:30.800 --> 00:22:34.520
And we don't have a plus system in USC.

00:22:34.760 --> 00:22:37.520
And so, like, but I want to give a couple people an A plus.

00:22:37.720 --> 00:22:43.780
But there's no way to really differentiate that besides telling them specifically yours was very good.

00:22:43.880 --> 00:22:46.600
Like, yours was one of the top papers.

00:22:46.600 --> 00:22:48.000
Which, I mean, I can tell them that.

00:22:48.040 --> 00:22:51.440
But there's no way to quantify that in our grade system.

00:22:51.440 --> 00:22:53.240
I do love that with our grading system.

00:22:53.380 --> 00:22:55.000
I mean, it does just give me more nuance, too.

00:22:55.060 --> 00:23:00.020
Because our department cares a lot more about grades and having some kind of variance.

00:23:00.300 --> 00:23:06.660
And so, like, you know, giving a C is able to do different kind of work for me than it would elsewhere or D or whatever else.

00:23:06.660 --> 00:23:07.940
Because it actually happens.

00:23:09.240 --> 00:23:10.980
But we also have the plus system.

00:23:10.980 --> 00:23:15.220
And it's very deliberately supposed to be super rare.

00:23:15.760 --> 00:23:22.800
Like, I might have, I might go an entire semester without a single person getting an A plus, you know, in a class.

00:23:23.420 --> 00:23:30.460
And then, and so, you know, like, I do feel like I'm marking some kind of real distinction when someone just knocks it out of the park.

00:23:30.520 --> 00:23:33.500
I've also had, like, classes where, like, two or three people got an A plus.

00:23:33.600 --> 00:23:35.620
And my God, are those fun classes to teach.

00:23:35.620 --> 00:23:42.540
But don't you guys have the same experience that I'm talking about, which is a failure of equivalence, right?

00:23:42.760 --> 00:23:46.440
Like, or the inadequacy of equivalence, like, at the level of the grade.

00:23:46.940 --> 00:23:48.940
Like, whatever the grade is, whatever it is.

00:23:48.980 --> 00:23:49.180
Yeah.

00:23:49.400 --> 00:23:52.960
You're just like, okay, this is a B student, and that's a B student.

00:23:53.060 --> 00:23:53.860
That's a B student?

00:23:54.020 --> 00:23:54.280
Yeah.

00:23:54.360 --> 00:23:57.440
I mean, I don't understand how this is that.

00:23:57.760 --> 00:24:01.940
Like, it just doesn't really, like, seriously make sense to me.

00:24:02.120 --> 00:24:04.920
Because there are B students that get it entirely through industry.

00:24:04.920 --> 00:24:08.180
It's like, they didn't turn, they turned everything in on time.

00:24:08.320 --> 00:24:11.260
Everything was, you know, sort of formatted correctly.

00:24:11.500 --> 00:24:13.180
You know, there was, like, they were there.

00:24:13.300 --> 00:24:14.300
They, you know, participated.

00:24:14.760 --> 00:24:18.600
And then there's the person who's the B student who's much more sort of, like.

00:24:18.620 --> 00:24:19.440
Who was the A student but didn't do the work.

00:24:19.840 --> 00:24:20.620
Yeah, exactly.

00:24:21.060 --> 00:24:21.400
Right?

00:24:21.620 --> 00:24:23.220
And, yeah, like, yeah, you're right.

00:24:23.360 --> 00:24:24.580
No two B students.

00:24:24.640 --> 00:24:27.000
I mean, you can typify and you can kind of create subdivisions.

00:24:27.080 --> 00:24:30.000
But even within then, there are, you know, inadequacies.

00:24:30.920 --> 00:24:31.120
Right.

00:24:31.160 --> 00:24:33.620
Or the people who slipped for a couple of weeks, right?

00:24:33.620 --> 00:24:34.620
Like, I think that's something.

00:24:34.620 --> 00:24:34.820
Yeah.

00:24:34.880 --> 00:24:35.760
What do you do with them?

00:24:36.380 --> 00:24:36.560
Yeah.

00:24:36.660 --> 00:24:37.420
Like, I don't know.

00:24:37.820 --> 00:24:44.520
I don't have a sense of equivalencies with which I'm comfortable to be able to say, this

00:24:44.520 --> 00:24:45.420
thing is like that thing.

00:24:45.480 --> 00:24:47.720
Even at the A level, the same thing is true.

00:24:48.240 --> 00:24:48.260
Right?

00:24:48.300 --> 00:24:51.120
Like, it doesn't matter what level we're talking about and what grade.

00:24:51.220 --> 00:24:56.580
But just my inability to really believe in the equivalencies between these is what makes

00:24:56.580 --> 00:24:58.500
me so uncomfortable and what makes me so uncomfortable with grades.

00:24:58.500 --> 00:25:04.540
It's like, I mean, I think I can say things like, well, this is good or this has promise

00:25:04.540 --> 00:25:07.140
or this is like, I can kind of descriptors.

00:25:07.540 --> 00:25:14.040
But as far as getting any kind of quantitative hierarchical feedback, like, I don't, like, I'm not sure

00:25:14.040 --> 00:25:15.160
that this is better than that.

00:25:15.260 --> 00:25:19.000
This is weirder than that or this is more out there than that or this is a less conventional

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:20.900
way of reading this thing than that thing.

00:25:21.300 --> 00:25:27.300
Well, I've also, because I'm so invested in how students engage the text, the how of the engagement

00:25:27.300 --> 00:25:32.140
and, like, you know, I'm perfectly comfortable with using very sort of probably frustratingly

00:25:32.140 --> 00:25:33.020
ambiguous language.

00:25:33.220 --> 00:25:38.160
Like, you are taking on the position of the master in a relationship to this text in your

00:25:38.160 --> 00:25:39.360
effort to explain it.

00:25:39.440 --> 00:25:44.960
And I want you to take on a position of hesitancy and exploration, act as if it is a, and I'm

00:25:44.960 --> 00:25:50.240
like, you know, like, I can, fortunately, I haven't had any student, like, react supposably

00:25:50.240 --> 00:25:55.600
to that kind of language and, like, be like, Dean, you know, how does, how can this be sort

00:25:55.600 --> 00:25:57.720
of kept consistent across the board?

00:25:57.780 --> 00:26:00.980
I'm like, no way, no, in no way can it, can it be.

00:26:01.280 --> 00:26:07.880
And yet it is so much more effective, like so much more powerful for me to use that kind

00:26:07.880 --> 00:26:08.280
of language.

00:26:08.380 --> 00:26:11.300
I never, I very rarely say, unless if it's good, I never say it's bad.

00:26:11.580 --> 00:26:12.800
I never say this is better than that.

00:26:12.860 --> 00:26:18.040
Unless if it's in relationship to their stuff, like you really let go.

00:26:18.140 --> 00:26:21.080
You, you were like way, this is way better because you were more patient.

00:26:21.080 --> 00:26:22.760
You allowed yourself to sit on this thing.

00:26:22.880 --> 00:26:26.800
You allowed yourself to like break this thing down and, and, you know, you're allowed to

00:26:26.800 --> 00:26:29.820
like make yours, make these kinds of connections that you weren't able to do before.

00:26:29.940 --> 00:26:31.680
So like for you, this is better.

00:26:31.680 --> 00:26:31.940
Right.

00:26:31.980 --> 00:26:36.180
But then I never feel like I have to compare it to other students, which is nice.

00:26:36.460 --> 00:26:36.640
Yeah.

00:26:36.760 --> 00:26:42.580
I feel like I reward curiosity a lot in the classroom and just effort too.

00:26:42.700 --> 00:26:48.320
It's like, even if they're not adept writers, if they're trying, like if they're reading my

00:26:48.320 --> 00:26:52.420
comments and they, they've made a good faith effort at attending to them and making those

00:26:52.420 --> 00:26:53.280
changes, I'm like.

00:26:53.500 --> 00:26:58.220
But that's a, but that's a good example of, of a very, very common problem.

00:26:58.220 --> 00:27:02.460
You have on the one hand, the student who has a great facility with language, but doesn't

00:27:02.460 --> 00:27:04.300
really exert very much effort.

00:27:04.700 --> 00:27:08.280
On the other hand, you have the one who's just not as good of a writer, but really tries

00:27:08.280 --> 00:27:08.960
really hard.

00:27:09.140 --> 00:27:15.600
And the idea that they're the same grade or the same, I mean, again, I'm not saying one's

00:27:15.600 --> 00:27:15.900
better than the other.

00:27:15.900 --> 00:27:20.520
I don't know which one is better than the other one, but like the notion of an equivalence

00:27:20.520 --> 00:27:24.800
that something like our grading system sets up just, it just doesn't seem.

00:27:25.080 --> 00:27:29.520
But it also depends on what you see the function of the grade and the class as doing.

00:27:29.640 --> 00:27:35.080
If it's a, if it's purely a gatekeeping function, if it's purely a, like, did you achieve a certain

00:27:35.080 --> 00:27:39.000
level of mastery of something, then I'd have a different orientation to it.

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:44.360
But I try to minimize that as much as possible that, you know, like my job isn't to ensure

00:27:44.360 --> 00:27:46.540
that you have learned a handful of things.

00:27:46.680 --> 00:27:53.640
My job is to ensure, or not even ensure, is to make it possible for you to engage something

00:27:53.640 --> 00:27:59.360
unfamiliar and, you know, and so like, if that's actually the goal of the class, yeah.

00:27:59.500 --> 00:28:04.260
So if that's actually the goal of the class, then that makes grading both in terms of like

00:28:04.260 --> 00:28:11.580
what kind of successes it's marking and in terms of like the function of it different than,

00:28:11.580 --> 00:28:16.900
you know, making sure that you've gotten over some kind of subject knowledge threshold.

00:28:17.540 --> 00:28:19.860
You've gotten your threshold concepts down.

00:28:20.360 --> 00:28:22.100
But it's hard when you're at, at least for me.

00:28:22.220 --> 00:28:27.320
I mean, and maybe this is just me being whiny, but like, I got 70 students this semester.

00:28:28.180 --> 00:28:29.520
Oh yeah, you can't do it with 70.

00:28:29.580 --> 00:28:30.160
No fucking way.

00:28:30.860 --> 00:28:45.020
I mean, I didn't mean to get us onto the grading thing, but that, but look, in many ways, that's

00:28:45.020 --> 00:28:47.100
an example in terms of the intellectual consciousness thing.

00:28:47.140 --> 00:28:51.980
It's like my discomfort in feeling like I need to have an account for this practice that

00:28:51.980 --> 00:28:56.700
I engage in literally like multiple times a week, just grading fricking quizzes.

00:28:57.400 --> 00:28:57.460
Yeah.

00:28:57.580 --> 00:29:02.300
But I mean, the grading thing fits what we're talking about here on, on two lines, both in

00:29:02.300 --> 00:29:06.040
terms of the intellectual consciousness or conscience that I'm just trying to be like,

00:29:06.120 --> 00:29:12.360
how do I grapple with this tool that I'm using to like make life livable in some kind of way?

00:29:12.360 --> 00:29:19.020
But then also that, that drive to find the certainty that, to find the grounds on which

00:29:19.020 --> 00:29:21.320
you can, can stabilize life.

00:29:21.320 --> 00:29:26.000
And you know, what you're kind of like getting at is that, you know, for you, that equivalency

00:29:26.000 --> 00:29:33.320
making model, that mathematical quantifying model that gives a lot of people certainty fundamentally

00:29:33.320 --> 00:29:35.020
unnerves you.

00:29:35.440 --> 00:29:36.500
It really does.

00:29:36.560 --> 00:29:36.780
Right.

00:29:36.880 --> 00:29:38.680
And that should be the thing that should make me feel better.

00:29:39.920 --> 00:29:40.360
Right.

00:29:40.620 --> 00:29:47.040
Well, to me, that, that drive for certainty always leads to, to stress and anxiety for,

00:29:47.140 --> 00:29:48.780
for grad students, for undergrads.

00:29:48.840 --> 00:29:54.920
Like when you're trying to comprehend a text, you're not going to be able to, especially if

00:29:54.920 --> 00:29:58.300
it's difficult, you're not going to be able to fully comprehend something on the first go.

00:29:58.940 --> 00:30:04.820
And so I've always stressed like a sort of sampling approach or like a kind of mosaic approach.

00:30:04.820 --> 00:30:09.660
Like if you can key into certain moments and leverage them for, for your writing, that's really

00:30:09.660 --> 00:30:10.540
all you need to do.

00:30:10.620 --> 00:30:14.040
And that's not based on a telos of certainty and comprehension.

00:30:14.240 --> 00:30:17.780
That's the other reason I teach Foucault for my first year students.

00:30:17.940 --> 00:30:22.640
I'm like, look, I'm teaching you the hardest thing I possibly can out of this textbook because

00:30:22.640 --> 00:30:24.380
I know no one's understanding it.

00:30:24.740 --> 00:30:26.240
Like that's the point, you know?

00:30:26.300 --> 00:30:30.380
And so if, if you feel like, oh, there are a bunch of smarter people in here that can understand

00:30:30.380 --> 00:30:31.140
it and I'm dumb.

00:30:31.600 --> 00:30:35.400
No, I promise you no one in this, no one in this room is understanding this.

00:30:35.560 --> 00:30:39.680
I don't pretend, you know, I think it's dangerous when I pretend like I understand it.

00:30:39.820 --> 00:30:43.500
But I, even at the basic levels, no one in this room is right now.

00:30:43.500 --> 00:30:46.380
So that's, know that that's what I want you to sit with.

00:30:46.420 --> 00:30:48.900
You're not failing by not understanding it.

00:30:49.280 --> 00:30:54.460
And another tactic for that, that I have kind of happened on in the course of teaching

00:30:54.460 --> 00:30:57.600
these classes is teaching bad movies.

00:30:58.380 --> 00:31:04.820
Like, you know, we did this movie Splice that's, it's just a bad movie, but there's a lot of

00:31:04.820 --> 00:31:06.820
interesting elements to it.

00:31:07.120 --> 00:31:13.820
So once you get over the fact that it's a bad movie and it forces them to kind of be like,

00:31:13.900 --> 00:31:17.940
okay, and especially with the majors, the majors had to spend 10 minutes in their responses

00:31:17.940 --> 00:31:19.920
like saying like, here's why it's bad.

00:31:19.980 --> 00:31:20.540
Here's why it's bad.

00:31:20.600 --> 00:31:20.940
And it is.

00:31:21.020 --> 00:31:24.880
And like next week we're doing RoboCop, another bad movie, right?

00:31:25.500 --> 00:31:27.880
But interesting things happen in there.

00:31:27.880 --> 00:31:33.220
Like once you get rid of this, that the goal of reading is to come up with a global judgment

00:31:33.220 --> 00:31:35.260
of the value of the thing.

00:31:35.260 --> 00:31:39.280
It's like our heritage of like our, our inheritance from new criticism.

00:31:39.540 --> 00:31:41.680
It's like, my God, could we do something else?

00:31:41.740 --> 00:31:44.480
Can we think in relation to the things that we read?

00:31:45.120 --> 00:31:49.180
And, you know, they all did the same kind of thing with the Splice thing that I did a

00:31:49.180 --> 00:31:49.900
couple of weeks ago.

00:31:49.900 --> 00:31:53.500
And I was like, okay, so you guys all agree that Splice is a bad movie.

00:31:53.620 --> 00:31:54.760
So fucking what?

