That's an unusual conjunction of values.

01:02:42.560 --> 01:02:47.300
Because of the unimportance of individual autonomy in relationship to the species, right?

01:02:47.720 --> 01:02:48.760
That's right, right?

01:02:48.860 --> 01:02:52.220
Like, so perhaps laughter will then have formed an alliance with wisdom.

01:02:52.340 --> 01:02:55.200
Perhaps only Gay Science will then be laughed.

01:02:55.820 --> 01:03:03.100
And, I mean, as an articulation of that sort of, I mean, think of it, Deleuze talks about it in terms of the innocence of the child, right?

01:03:03.160 --> 01:03:04.960
Is the stage of the child.

01:03:05.040 --> 01:03:16.100
It's like, that's this blind irresponsibility to laugh at oneself out of a sense of the whole truth, which is like, I mean, everything is permitted, right?

01:03:16.100 --> 01:03:30.460
I mean, there are consequences, I mean, there are consequences, I mean, there are mistakes, you know, but it's like, that's, that's sort of, at least for me, an incredibly invigorating sense of individual irresponsibility, you know, irrespective of it.

01:03:30.460 --> 01:03:33.640
From the perspective of life, right?

01:03:33.820 --> 01:03:40.320
Which, you know, like he has the later aphorism about, you know, views from a distance, you know, from a distance.

01:03:40.500 --> 01:03:41.880
This is aphorism 15.

01:03:42.140 --> 01:03:48.560
And it's like, right, life as the mountain, you know, makes everything look, you know, pretty beautiful.

01:03:48.560 --> 01:03:53.820
And then I'm going to go climb Mount Life, I'm going to get up there and like, fuck, this kind of sucks from up here.

01:03:54.260 --> 01:03:58.320
Like, this is a great perspective for life, but I am clearly not just life.

01:03:58.420 --> 01:03:59.020
This is boring.

01:03:59.120 --> 01:04:03.520
This thing moves on the level of eons and mass slaughter and bloodletting.

01:04:03.700 --> 01:04:07.200
And, you know, I'm going to come back down to my little, you know, cave.

01:04:07.400 --> 01:04:14.260
But back to the first aphorism, though, it seems that they're very distinctly like two kinds of laughter, right?

01:04:14.340 --> 01:04:22.760
There's the, like, the laughter of the Gay Science, the laughter of this laughter that has allied itself with wisdom is not a corrective laughter.

01:04:23.140 --> 01:04:31.140
It's not, it's not the laughter at the teacher of the purpose of existence, right?

01:04:31.240 --> 01:04:36.840
Like, there's that kind of ebb and flow, you know, launch, like the teacher of the purpose of existence,

01:04:37.220 --> 01:04:42.740
provides a certainty that allows people to latch onto it and provide purpose for life, right?

01:04:42.940 --> 01:04:44.460
It gives that kind of confidence.

01:04:44.740 --> 01:04:48.660
And then the corrective laughter looks at it and be like, what fucking dumb shits?

01:04:48.740 --> 01:04:49.840
You believed in God?

01:04:49.900 --> 01:04:52.140
All of you people died for God, right?

01:04:52.240 --> 01:04:58.680
And then, you know, but at a certain point, that's healthy for life up to a certain point.

01:04:58.680 --> 01:05:03.440
But it becomes sickly for life if it slips into nihilism, I guess nihilism, right?

01:05:03.860 --> 01:05:09.340
And you need that return of a kind of, you know, a purpose of life.

01:05:09.380 --> 01:05:22.960
But this laughter at the self, the laugh at the whole truth, it's almost like a laughter at myself in the delight of needing that certainty and the absurdity of that.

01:05:22.960 --> 01:05:28.440
Like, can I delight in the necessity and the absurdity of the certainty that I seek?

01:05:28.840 --> 01:05:32.840
And which seems to also, I mean, for me, this is always the wrinkle that I want to add on to it.

01:05:33.680 --> 01:05:35.900
Yeah, the wrinkle I always want to add on to it.

01:05:35.900 --> 01:05:44.840
And, like, the beauty and the tragedy of allowing that certainty to become another certainty, to become, like, right?

01:05:45.320 --> 01:06:00.360
You know, that seems to be the difference between that, that gay laughter, that, or the Gay Science, and by the way, not saying then that the Gay Science is better than, you know, the corrective laughter, right?

01:06:00.680 --> 01:06:04.200
You wouldn't be laughing if you were saying that Gay Science was better.

01:06:04.780 --> 01:06:06.220
Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:06:07.000 --> 01:06:08.980
It would just, that would just be your certainty.

01:06:09.660 --> 01:06:14.700
Right, I think that all that you say is, like, that's a tune I can dance to, or I want to learn how to dance to.

01:06:14.820 --> 01:06:19.160
Like, I want to live, I mean, that's for me, you know, I've told you guys in terms of this book, like, I want to live like that.

01:06:19.640 --> 01:06:29.000
I aspire to that level of irresponsibility, and I make, like, you know, little steps along the way, you know, there's still too much that seems heavy, right?

01:06:29.120 --> 01:06:33.760
Like, and I don't know how to, you know, jujitsu it yet.

01:06:34.660 --> 01:06:36.000
Right, yeah, right.

01:06:36.160 --> 01:06:38.320
Because we can't live from the perspective of life.

01:06:38.400 --> 01:06:41.700
We can only live from the perspective of the kind of life that we are.

01:06:41.700 --> 01:06:52.480
But is the goal then to eventually, like, not access, but reach on that same sort of frequency, life?

01:06:52.800 --> 01:06:55.820
Like, is that the goal of the overman or the breakthrough?

01:06:56.340 --> 01:07:01.700
Like, the sort of liberation from the human as opposed to of the human, you know?

01:07:01.700 --> 01:07:09.980
My guess would be, like, the kind of, I mean, that's where the overman, I don't think the overman's like a leader, you know?

01:07:10.280 --> 01:07:10.480
No.

01:07:10.560 --> 01:07:13.000
It's like, the overman will come and everyone will follow.

01:07:13.160 --> 01:07:16.020
It's like, no, the overman's popping up in various ways.

01:07:16.020 --> 01:07:16.860
He's just there.

01:07:17.520 --> 01:07:17.800
Right.

01:07:18.000 --> 01:07:19.260
He's probably just alone.

01:07:19.720 --> 01:07:23.700
Well, this Gay Science is in some ways just the over, is the overman.

01:07:23.700 --> 01:07:35.620
Because the Gay Science would be the, to render it the way that I said before, to sort of, like, delight in both the corrective laughter and the reason for existence.

01:07:36.200 --> 01:07:41.160
And to sort of, I mean, to affirm that would be to affirm one's own self-overcoming, right?

01:07:41.300 --> 01:07:44.980
To say, here's my certainty, here's my laughter at my certainty.

01:07:44.980 --> 01:07:50.480
And their conjunction is its own self-mutation, its own self-becoming.

01:07:51.960 --> 01:07:55.920
That's, that is the overcoming of man.

01:07:56.040 --> 01:07:57.420
That is literally the overcoming of man.

01:07:57.480 --> 01:08:00.440
Now, it's not some conscious thing that I can do or become.

01:08:00.580 --> 01:08:02.440
Like, I can't, you know, I don't become the overman.

01:08:02.580 --> 01:08:06.840
But that's certainly, like, a dynamic or another name for it would just be the eternal return.

01:08:07.260 --> 01:08:12.900
Like, in Zarathustra, the terminology is always, like, your dream should be to give birth to the overman.

01:08:13.040 --> 01:08:14.460
It's never about being the overman.

01:08:14.700 --> 01:08:16.480
It's about giving birth to it.

01:08:16.660 --> 01:08:21.040
And especially in this context, there are a number of different passages that maybe we can look at next time.

01:08:21.220 --> 01:08:26.900
But where he's like, look, the inheritors of things are way more important than the things themselves.

01:08:27.060 --> 01:08:29.500
Where it's like the grandparents, it's like.

01:08:29.600 --> 01:08:30.580
Yeah, I love that.

01:08:30.880 --> 01:08:31.480
And the grandchildren, too.

01:08:31.780 --> 01:08:38.460
And oftentimes, the grandchildren are, like, what he sees as the inheritors of a particular disposition.

01:08:39.100 --> 01:08:42.860
That disposition looks really different in the grandchildren than it is in the parents.

01:08:42.860 --> 01:08:49.360
So it's like, you don't even know what things, you know, are going to be taken up as your disposition.

01:08:49.360 --> 01:08:52.040
That's what, you know, the unconscious instinct stuff.

01:08:52.580 --> 01:08:56.800
You need a geology of morals, not a biology of morals in some ways, right?

01:08:57.140 --> 01:08:57.200
Yeah.

01:08:57.200 --> 01:08:59.620
Just that, you know, like, this shit moves slow.

01:08:59.820 --> 01:09:00.000
Right.

01:09:00.100 --> 01:09:00.320
Yeah.

01:09:01.140 --> 01:09:01.380
Yeah.

01:09:02.580 --> 01:09:08.220
Prehistory as the longest and most important stage of human development, to put it in, you know, Nietzsche's terms.

01:09:08.360 --> 01:09:12.220
But, like, there's another passage in the first aphorism.

01:09:12.500 --> 01:09:15.620
It's only, like, maybe ten lines down on the very first one.

01:09:16.080 --> 01:09:18.160
And this is sort of, like, what we've already been talking about.

01:09:18.240 --> 01:09:22.680
But there's a trick about, you know, like, hatred doesn't hurt or evil doesn't hurt the human.

01:09:22.760 --> 01:09:28.680
In fact, it's probably good in a certain kind of way in terms of preserving the species.

01:09:28.680 --> 01:09:31.540
But there's a twist here that I kind of want to focus on.

01:09:31.980 --> 01:09:42.880
Hatred, delight in the misfortunes of others, the lust to rob and rule, and whatever else is called evil, all belong to the amazing economy of the preservation of the species.

01:09:43.180 --> 01:09:51.940
An economy which is certainly costly, wasteful, and on the whole, most foolish, but still proven to have preserved our race so far.

01:09:51.940 --> 01:09:59.820
I no longer know whether you, my dear fellow man and neighbor, are even capable of living in a way that is damaging to the species.

01:09:59.980 --> 01:10:02.820
But it's about the inefficient, this inefficient economy.

01:10:03.280 --> 01:10:09.440
Like, and not just, like, it's not just that, oh, well, it's been inefficient and it's been costly, but it works.

01:10:09.500 --> 01:10:12.760
So we just keep old Betsy running and, you know, maybe we could become more inefficient.

01:10:12.840 --> 01:10:18.880
There's no, like, there's the value of the waste, the overabundance, the superfluousness.

01:10:19.000 --> 01:10:21.920
Like, that has its own function.

01:10:22.300 --> 01:10:24.640
Makes me think of, like, the decadence of the fruit, right?

01:10:24.700 --> 01:10:28.620
Of, like, in the beginning of the, is that the, um, Beyond Good and Evil?

01:10:29.040 --> 01:10:30.360
Yeah, Beyond Good and Evil, I think.

01:10:30.440 --> 01:10:31.580
Yeah, Beyond Good and Evil.

01:10:31.700 --> 01:10:33.500
My fruit is too rough for you, don't blame the tree.

01:10:33.500 --> 01:10:41.100
Yeah, but, like, but it's also that the tree, like, yields so much fruit and so much rot and so much decadence.

01:10:41.280 --> 01:10:47.040
And then, but the one little interesting thing that comes out of it made all of that waste worthwhile.

01:11:03.500 --> 01:11:13.680
And then, and then, and then, and then, and, and then, and then, and then, and then.
